WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.964 --> 00:00:02.410
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:08.200 --> 00:00:13.520
-How do native peoples perform
and protect their sovereignty?

00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:15.040
We heard the last
panel about how

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:18.170
they do so via legal
and judicial means

00:00:18.170 --> 00:00:21.770
in courts, both
Supreme and small.

00:00:21.770 --> 00:00:26.430
And we heard how complicated
that process was, and is,

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:28.290
about struggles
with federal courts,

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:31.290
about the tensions between
tribal, and federal courts,

00:00:31.290 --> 00:00:34.460
and about the tensions
between being a tribal judge,

00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:38.220
on the one hand, and being a
federal judge, on the other.

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:42.280
It is all too easy to presume
that Native politics means

00:00:42.280 --> 00:00:44.610
Native defeat.

00:00:44.610 --> 00:00:47.410
But the history and the present
reality of Native politics

00:00:47.410 --> 00:00:49.000
shows us otherwise.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.340
We heard just a
few evenings ago,

00:00:51.340 --> 00:00:54.340
during Kristiana
Kahakauwila's talk,

00:00:54.340 --> 00:00:56.200
that Native Hawaiians
may soon come

00:00:56.200 --> 00:01:00.250
into repossession of important
indigenous water rights.

00:01:00.250 --> 00:01:02.250
Those who have
visited Taos Pueblo,

00:01:02.250 --> 00:01:07.190
will recognize that, in 1970,
Taos Pueblo successfully

00:01:07.190 --> 00:01:10.780
culminated a long-term
lobbying campaign

00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:15.310
with the return of its sacred
Blue Lake, land and waterscape,

00:01:15.310 --> 00:01:17.550
in the Act of 1970.

00:01:17.550 --> 00:01:20.200
And today I note that
our keynote address

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:24.070
is being given by Rob
Porter of the Seneca Nation.

00:01:24.070 --> 00:01:28.310
And the Seneca Nation,
in 1842, successfully

00:01:28.310 --> 00:01:32.270
reversed critical portions of
the fraudulent Buffalo Creek

00:01:32.270 --> 00:01:39.400
Treaty of 1838, which created,
in that successful reversal,

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:45.220
the two-- the three,
excuse me, reservations

00:01:45.220 --> 00:01:50.520
on which the Seneca Nation
lives, thrives, and prospers

00:01:50.520 --> 00:01:52.170
today.

00:01:52.170 --> 00:01:55.390
We're going to talk about those
more political, less judicial,

00:01:55.390 --> 00:01:58.570
aspects of native politics
and empowerment today.

00:01:58.570 --> 00:02:03.040
And we've got three amazing
panelists with whom to do so.

00:02:03.040 --> 00:02:06.310
We're going to proceed
in alphabetical order,

00:02:06.310 --> 00:02:09.460
Karen Diver, to my
left, currently serves

00:02:09.460 --> 00:02:12.530
as the Special Assistant to the
President for Native American

00:02:12.530 --> 00:02:14.760
Affairs at the
White House, having

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:18.020
been appointed to that
position by President Obama.

00:02:18.020 --> 00:02:21.380
She previously served nine years
as chairwoman of the Fond du

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:23.510
Lac Band of Lake
Superior Chippewa,

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:28.360
where she oversaw a workforce
of over 2,000 employees

00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:31.120
for the second largest
employer in northern Minnesota.

00:02:31.120 --> 00:02:33.430
She is uniquely
positioned to speak

00:02:33.430 --> 00:02:36.340
toward internal domestic
tribal governance,

00:02:36.340 --> 00:02:41.320
as well as, national
politics in Indian Affairs.

00:02:41.320 --> 00:02:44.610
John Dossett, to her left,
is the General Counsel

00:02:44.610 --> 00:02:48.550
to the National Congress
of American Indians, NCAI.

00:02:48.550 --> 00:02:50.830
And his work includes
legal, legislative,

00:02:50.830 --> 00:02:52.840
and intergovernmental
issues relating

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:55.190
to the rights of
tribal governments.

00:02:55.190 --> 00:03:01.550
He has served in his
position since 1997.

00:03:01.550 --> 00:03:05.370
And finally, to his
left, Sylvia McAdam

00:03:05.370 --> 00:03:08.670
is from the Treaty 6 lands,
and a direct descendant

00:03:08.670 --> 00:03:11.050
of Treaty People.

00:03:11.050 --> 00:03:15.550
She is nêhiyaw and Nakawe and
speaks fluently in nêhiyaw.

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:18.220
McAdam is best
known as a cofounder

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:21.780
of the global grassroots
movement called,

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:25.970
Idle No More, which seeks to
assert the inherent indigenous

00:03:25.970 --> 00:03:29.470
rights to its sovereignty, and
re-institute traditional laws,

00:03:29.470 --> 00:03:33.600
and nation-to-nation treaties by
protecting the lands and waters

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:35.640
from corporate destruction.

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.570
We're going to begin
with Karen Diver,

00:03:38.570 --> 00:03:40.503
thanks for being with us.

00:03:40.503 --> 00:03:41.830
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:46.970 --> 00:03:49.440
-Good morning.

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:50.134
Yeah.

00:03:50.134 --> 00:03:51.556
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:51.556 --> 00:03:56.830
--[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]
I'm Karen Diver,

00:03:56.830 --> 00:03:59.680
Chairwoman Emeritus of the
Fond du Lac of Lake Superior

00:03:59.680 --> 00:04:00.270
Chippewa.

00:04:00.270 --> 00:04:02.980
It is primarily
in that role today

00:04:02.980 --> 00:04:06.610
that I'm sharing some remarks
with you, not necessarily

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:08.650
that of the White House,
although I hang around

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:12.210
there a little bit, as well.

00:04:12.210 --> 00:04:16.350
So I usually tell people that
now that I'm a bit removed

00:04:16.350 --> 00:04:20.019
from being a tribal
chairwoman, that I

00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:23.160
have a little bit of
post-traumatic stress syndrome,

00:04:23.160 --> 00:04:25.890
and I'm thinking there should
be some kind of support

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:29.710
group for former
elected tribal leaders.

00:04:29.710 --> 00:04:32.750
You know, they say, all
politics is personal,

00:04:32.750 --> 00:04:36.890
well it's way different
when it's your aunties,

00:04:36.890 --> 00:04:39.276
and that they can walk
right into your door.

00:04:39.276 --> 00:04:41.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:45.220
So I'm also really delighted
to be back here in Cambridge.

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:46.890
My year at the
Harvard Kennedy School

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:49.350
is actually one of the
most fulfilling years

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:52.460
that I have ever had the
privilege to be a part of,

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:55.000
particularly because
of HUNAP and getting

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.430
to know such bright, committed,
young, Native individuals.

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:03.430
I came as a little bit and of an
older student, so I was auntie.

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:05.720
I was the one that
actually brought real food

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:06.820
to the potlucks.

00:05:06.820 --> 00:05:08.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:13.050
Which made me a rare commodity.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:14.730
There's people here
who ate that food.

00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:16.152
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:18.050 --> 00:05:19.590
Why did I come to
Kennedy School?

00:05:19.590 --> 00:05:21.590
I came to the Kennedy
School because I

00:05:21.590 --> 00:05:24.140
was interested in learning
more from the Harvard

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:26.640
Project on American Indian
Economic Development.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.490
Really one of the
only institutions

00:05:28.490 --> 00:05:31.550
of higher learning that looked
at what does best practices

00:05:31.550 --> 00:05:34.570
look like in Indian
country, around governance

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:36.730
and economic development.

00:05:36.730 --> 00:05:40.630
I had saw my tribal community
go from an institution that

00:05:40.630 --> 00:05:43.990
was very small, less
than 80 employees,

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:46.320
had a hard time
sometimes making payroll,

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:50.350
and had to pick between
payroll and the light bill.

00:05:50.350 --> 00:05:53.640
And overtime-- just
extraordinary poverty.

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:59.820
Was the product of many
of my family members,

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:03.130
kind of participating, and
having federal Indian policy

00:06:03.130 --> 00:06:04.540
impact their lives.

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:07.180
My dad was a
boarding school kid,

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.820
so he was taken away from
his family at age six,

00:06:09.820 --> 00:06:11.940
with his brother, and
didn't really see them again

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:14.690
until they were eight
years old, lost his fluency

00:06:14.690 --> 00:06:17.940
in the language, but never
forgot who his people were,

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:19.760
and where he came from.

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:22.537
My family chose to go away
on the relocation program

00:06:22.537 --> 00:06:24.620
because they knew they had
to feed their children,

00:06:24.620 --> 00:06:28.180
and in my small town, you just
didn't hire Native people back

00:06:28.180 --> 00:06:32.010
then for the full-time jobs, the
good living-wage jobs, always

00:06:32.010 --> 00:06:33.985
day labor and on the edge.

00:06:33.985 --> 00:06:36.880
So I had the benefit of
being able to grow up

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:40.270
in an urban area, but what
my parents did for me is,

00:06:40.270 --> 00:06:41.820
they put all four
of their children

00:06:41.820 --> 00:06:44.690
through 12 years
of private school.

00:06:44.690 --> 00:06:46.420
They put their money
where their values

00:06:46.420 --> 00:06:47.930
were, which was in education.

00:06:47.930 --> 00:06:51.210
So as I grew, and wanted to
make a better bigger impact

00:06:51.210 --> 00:06:53.660
in my career, I knew
I had to learn more,

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:55.910
and I came here to learn it.

00:06:55.910 --> 00:06:59.520
I went back home, and
started working for my tribe.

00:06:59.520 --> 00:07:01.950
I worked as the director
of special projects

00:07:01.950 --> 00:07:05.210
doing lots of different things,
a lot of program development,

00:07:05.210 --> 00:07:07.050
administrative work.

00:07:07.050 --> 00:07:09.270
And when the job opened
up as the chairperson

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:11.560
I thought I would give it a try.

00:07:11.560 --> 00:07:13.340
My motives were
probably a little bit

00:07:13.340 --> 00:07:16.240
different than previous
tribal chair people, in that,

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:18.200
I was mostly
interested in building

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:21.180
the institution of
governance, and building

00:07:21.180 --> 00:07:23.310
an active citizenry.

00:07:23.310 --> 00:07:26.300
Much just to my dismay,
when you start doing that,

00:07:26.300 --> 00:07:29.600
they often practice
it on you, first.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:30.770
But that's OK, right?

00:07:30.770 --> 00:07:33.040
That's the stuff that
thick skin is made of,

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:36.680
and it's for the greater good.

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:39.900
So, the lesson I wanted to
work with my community on,

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:43.490
is this balance of
internal, versus external.

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:46.610
Very much Indian politics
in the home rule community

00:07:46.610 --> 00:07:48.880
is about, how is
what you're going

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:52.800
to do in your elected office,
how does that benefit me?

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:54.900
How does this increase
my housing options?

00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:57.350
How does this increase
my employment options?

00:07:57.350 --> 00:07:59.550
And where really siloed
in Indian country,

00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:01.840
I mean, the government
did a real good job

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:04.380
in making reservations,
they're very close,

00:08:04.380 --> 00:08:07.340
they're very cloistered,
they're gulags.

00:08:07.340 --> 00:08:10.370
And they intended-- the
purpose and the intention

00:08:10.370 --> 00:08:13.560
of isolation of Native
communities, it worked.

00:08:13.560 --> 00:08:16.450
We have a tribal people
now whom by and large look

00:08:16.450 --> 00:08:21.480
to their tribal governments
for 100% of their daily needs,

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:22.860
everything from
their employment,

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:25.310
to their energy assistance,
to their recreational

00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:28.640
opportunities, to access to
their language and culture,

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:30.680
and on, and on, and on, and on.

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:34.070
But how does that actually
relate to a broader world

00:08:34.070 --> 00:08:35.400
that we're a part of?

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:38.490
And is that strategy OK
for Natives long term?

00:08:38.490 --> 00:08:40.890
Well, we saw it changing
when we became more

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:43.090
of an economic entity, right?

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:45.480
So tribes were able
to take advantage

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.200
of learning Federal Indian Law,
and learning more about how

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:52.570
our governance relates to
the larger federal picture,

00:08:52.570 --> 00:08:56.240
and we found a niche in the
market that allowed tribes to,

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:59.040
under civil regulatory
jurisdiction,

00:08:59.040 --> 00:09:03.060
undertake a form of economic
development called, gaming.

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:06.400
That brought us to the attention
of broader communities in a way

00:09:06.400 --> 00:09:09.110
that we had pretty
much not had before.

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:11.640
It was really easy to ignore
Native communities when

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:14.310
we were poor and dependent,
just stay on your reservation,

00:09:14.310 --> 00:09:15.844
and stay out of our way.

00:09:15.844 --> 00:09:17.260
Well, it's a whole
different thing

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:20.310
if you fast forward through
becoming economic entities,

00:09:20.310 --> 00:09:23.800
and starting to become the
largest employer in your area,

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:25.870
if not a large
swath of your state.

00:09:25.870 --> 00:09:29.270
Now people are paying
attention in a different way.

00:09:29.270 --> 00:09:30.700
To me that really
meant we needed

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:34.640
to do some intention-- turn
our attention internally,

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:36.620
to our systems,
that we grow them.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:39.280
To be able to have the
capacity to take on this larger

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:41.232
role and broader communities.

00:09:41.232 --> 00:09:42.940
But we also needed to
get a little better

00:09:42.940 --> 00:09:46.910
about communicating
what it is we are,

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:51.190
why we do what we do, how does
that matter to our people,

00:09:51.190 --> 00:09:54.960
internally, within our home rule
community, and our citizenry,

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:57.440
and how does that relate
to the rest of the world?

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:00.690
All of a sudden we're bumping
into these multijurisdictional

00:10:00.690 --> 00:10:01.540
issues.

00:10:01.540 --> 00:10:03.670
Whether it's growing
our police department,

00:10:03.670 --> 00:10:07.490
and figuring out how to do
mutual-aid agreements so that

00:10:07.490 --> 00:10:11.530
we can serve our joint
citizens just as well.

00:10:11.530 --> 00:10:13.820
The panel previous
to me, actually,

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:18.290
was a good foundation for,
kind of the way I looked

00:10:18.290 --> 00:10:19.610
at what tribal governance is.

00:10:19.610 --> 00:10:23.250
And, you know, people confuse
race with political status.

00:10:23.250 --> 00:10:25.220
And that was a
constant mantra that I

00:10:25.220 --> 00:10:27.820
had to have over and
over again, whether it

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:31.110
was with townships, or cities,
or counties, or the state.

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:34.810
Of saying, my citizens
are still your citizens.

00:10:34.810 --> 00:10:37.670
They have an absolute
right to service delivery,

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.960
and your attention, and
for you to understand

00:10:39.960 --> 00:10:41.920
what their needs
are, and balance them

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:43.700
with the rest of
your constituency.

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:47.780
You do not get to abdicate your
responsibility to your citizens

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:49.800
just because they are tribal.

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:52.250
I will share that
with you, but I

00:10:52.250 --> 00:10:55.010
will hold you accountable
for your service delivery.

00:10:55.010 --> 00:10:57.290
You don't get to not
send your police officers

00:10:57.290 --> 00:11:00.380
to the reservation, when
were a Public Law 280

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:03.560
state, which says, that their
state criminal jurisdiction

00:11:03.560 --> 00:11:04.410
that rules.

00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:06.000
So even though I'm
not a lawyer, I

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.161
had to play one on TV regularly.

00:11:08.161 --> 00:11:08.661
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:13.452
It was called the news. [LAUGHS]

00:11:13.452 --> 00:11:14.871
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:16.770 --> 00:11:18.680
Because I had to be
able to articulate

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:21.330
to those other jurisdictions,
and to those other

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:26.250
stakeholders, why what happened
in my piece of Indian country

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:30.180
mattered to them, and why my
citizens continued to matter,

00:11:30.180 --> 00:11:32.480
and that we were not
going to allow ourselves

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:34.450
to be ignored anymore.

00:11:34.450 --> 00:11:39.720
But we do, and we are, and
it's very selective, right?

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:41.440
They look at our
economic success

00:11:41.440 --> 00:11:43.980
and say, well, why don't
we get to have casinos.

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:48.480
And I would say back, well,
we are a political entities.

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:52.620
You're confusing our race
with our political status.

00:11:52.620 --> 00:11:54.414
We have a different
jurisdiction.

00:11:54.414 --> 00:11:55.830
And then, generally,
I would point

00:11:55.830 --> 00:11:58.510
out they didn't share
250 years of oppression,

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:04.100
poverty, and everything
else, too, but, you know.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:08.217
Politics is
personal, even to me.

00:12:08.217 --> 00:12:09.800
But then there was
the broader picture

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:13.700
of talking to my citizens about
what could they expect out

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:17.050
of their elected leadership
that went a little bit beyond,

00:12:17.050 --> 00:12:18.730
what can I do in
the home community?

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:21.370
Because I had all of
these multijuristictional

00:12:21.370 --> 00:12:25.130
relationships to
manage, as well as,

00:12:25.130 --> 00:12:28.330
making sure that the
2,200 employees did

00:12:28.330 --> 00:12:31.720
service delivery, and economic
development, really well.

00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:34.500
And I would have my home rule
community say to me, well,

00:12:34.500 --> 00:12:36.860
why are you going to DC, Karen?

00:12:36.860 --> 00:12:37.770
What about here?

00:12:37.770 --> 00:12:40.540
How are you taken care of here?

00:12:40.540 --> 00:12:43.500
And so the communication
started to begin, and we--

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:47.280
I ramped up my own
personal transparency,

00:12:47.280 --> 00:12:49.960
through regular open meetings
with our own citizens,

00:12:49.960 --> 00:12:54.225
and newspaper articles, and
tried to let them know why.

00:12:54.225 --> 00:12:55.720
Why do I go to DC?

00:12:55.720 --> 00:12:57.330
Why do I talk to
federal officials?

00:12:57.330 --> 00:13:00.740
Why do I talk to
our legislators?

00:13:00.740 --> 00:13:03.250
Why does that matter in
the home rule community?

00:13:03.250 --> 00:13:06.450
How do we broaden the scope
of our active citizenry

00:13:06.450 --> 00:13:11.190
to say, out there matters
as much to us, as here.

00:13:11.190 --> 00:13:14.870
And that was the story we
really needed to get out.

00:13:14.870 --> 00:13:17.760
Obviously, we look to
Congress to help us

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:20.820
with some of the poor
decisions of the Court.

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:24.490
Congress has plenary
power, obviously provide

00:13:24.490 --> 00:13:28.270
a legislative fix to some of the
poor federal, and Supreme Court

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:32.142
decisions, [INAUDIBLE],
land into trust issues.

00:13:32.142 --> 00:13:34.310
A very poor ruling
out of the courts

00:13:34.310 --> 00:13:35.970
that really narrowed
the definition

00:13:35.970 --> 00:13:38.670
of the types of lands that
the Department of Interior

00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:39.810
can take into trusts.

00:13:39.810 --> 00:13:42.010
We need a legislative fix.

00:13:42.010 --> 00:13:45.370
Some of the inroads, or,
not even the inroads,

00:13:45.370 --> 00:13:48.620
incursions into Indian
Child Welfare Act.

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:50.250
That's going to be
a federal response,

00:13:50.250 --> 00:13:52.910
either through federal
agency rule-making,

00:13:52.910 --> 00:14:00.460
or additional activity
out of Congress.

00:14:00.460 --> 00:14:03.740
One of the things we started
with, was real basic.

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:05.950
You can understand
as a tribal person

00:14:05.950 --> 00:14:11.680
why you need to be engaged
in tribal politics,

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:16.900
why do they need to be engaged
in the broader world politics.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:19.430
And we got out the vote.

00:14:19.430 --> 00:14:21.360
We got out the vote
in such a big way

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:23.750
that we swung local elections.

00:14:23.750 --> 00:14:26.180
If you talk to Al
Franken, he will tell you,

00:14:26.180 --> 00:14:28.710
and conf-- and say that the
Indian vote helped get him

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:30.100
in office.

00:14:30.100 --> 00:14:33.880
As politics has gotten
more polarized, and-- nah,

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:35.503
that's not happening, right?

00:14:35.503 --> 00:14:37.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:37.770 --> 00:14:39.620
Smaller constituencies
can matter

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:42.220
more as we become more divided.

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:45.800
So the voices are even
more, and more important.

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:50.150
Senator Franken
won by 312 votes.

00:14:50.150 --> 00:14:53.040
312 votes.

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:55.830
We registered more voters
just at Fond du Lac,

00:14:55.830 --> 00:14:58.320
new voters that year.

00:14:58.320 --> 00:15:00.870
We gave them rides,
we had free transit,

00:15:00.870 --> 00:15:02.910
we did voter
registration drives,

00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:07.060
we had, I voted, stickers,
made into our language.

00:15:07.060 --> 00:15:09.820
And they became a thing of
pride to wear in our community

00:15:09.820 --> 00:15:11.900
for people to vote.

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:14.660
We told them that your
legislators are the ones that

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:16.760
are your voice at
the table, and rather

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:20.630
than fix things that are
broken, they can be proactive.

00:15:20.630 --> 00:15:24.700
We challenged Senator Franken
to become a member of the Senate

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:26.950
Committee on Indian Affairs,
because we hadn't had

00:15:26.950 --> 00:15:29.780
one out of Minnesota, a member.

00:15:29.780 --> 00:15:31.970
And there's 11
tribes in Minnesota.

00:15:31.970 --> 00:15:34.590
And that we wanted him to know
that, if he wanted our support,

00:15:34.590 --> 00:15:36.990
we expected him to be
a part of the voice.

00:15:36.990 --> 00:15:39.250
And he did it, and
he's there, and he's

00:15:39.250 --> 00:15:43.040
fighting for Indian
people on that committee.

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:45.210
As tribal governance
has grown and taken

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:48.740
on more responsibility,
we're starting

00:15:48.740 --> 00:15:51.170
to see more and more
that, what you're

00:15:51.170 --> 00:15:54.370
electing as a local
tribal leader,

00:15:54.370 --> 00:15:57.950
isn't just somebody who
manages the governance,

00:15:57.950 --> 00:15:59.910
you're electing an advocate.

00:15:59.910 --> 00:16:02.590
And so we're trying
to push the idea of,

00:16:02.590 --> 00:16:05.090
don't just vote because that
someone is your relative,

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:08.070
and you think that means
your family will do better

00:16:08.070 --> 00:16:09.870
under a new regime.

00:16:09.870 --> 00:16:13.160
But they are able to articulate
kind of the global needs

00:16:13.160 --> 00:16:15.240
of your community.

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:18.050
How many children--
do we see spikes

00:16:18.050 --> 00:16:21.050
in our local counties
of children being placed

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:23.280
in out-of-home placement?

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:25.840
What kind of economic
impact do we make?

00:16:25.840 --> 00:16:29.700
Are they able to articulate
that a rising tide really

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:32.560
does lift all boats, and a
healthy tribal community,

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:35.420
in my case, contributed
well over $300 million

00:16:35.420 --> 00:16:38.590
to a local role economy.

00:16:38.590 --> 00:16:41.360
You need to have that advocacy.

00:16:41.360 --> 00:16:44.980
Sequestration, actually,
was one of the things that

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:47.280
came to my people, that
was really able for them

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:49.310
to understand, how
does this affect me?

00:16:49.310 --> 00:16:53.020
When we talked about, if
we're not an advocate in DC,

00:16:53.020 --> 00:16:55.390
here's what will happen in
the home rule community,

00:16:55.390 --> 00:16:57.620
in terms of our
service delivery.

00:16:57.620 --> 00:17:00.460
We expect these things
to be able to not

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:02.090
be able to continue.

00:17:02.090 --> 00:17:04.300
Everything from elder
Meals On Wheels,

00:17:04.300 --> 00:17:07.750
to home health care
aides, to Head Start,

00:17:07.750 --> 00:17:09.450
and on, and on, and on.

00:17:09.450 --> 00:17:13.510
Now Washington,
DC, feels very real

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:15.880
when you're talking
about our loved ones.

00:17:15.880 --> 00:17:18.920
The other part is, maybe not
as sexy, but just as important,

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:22.741
talking to our community about
the census, and participation,

00:17:22.741 --> 00:17:23.990
and different data collection.

00:17:23.990 --> 00:17:27.589
Data collection is
terrible in Indian country.

00:17:27.589 --> 00:17:30.620
We are tired of people tracking
us, they track our blood,

00:17:30.620 --> 00:17:34.240
they track where we live, they
track who our ancestors are.

00:17:34.240 --> 00:17:36.200
Would you quit
tracking us already?

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:38.050
Well, here's a
tribal leader saying,

00:17:38.050 --> 00:17:39.530
I need you to fill
out the census,

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:42.290
and tell some people, you
know, everything about you

00:17:42.290 --> 00:17:45.640
that really is none of their
business, but yet it matters.

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:49.220
So we had our own census people,
members from our own community,

00:17:49.220 --> 00:17:51.400
that could go in and
make our families

00:17:51.400 --> 00:17:53.520
feel comfortable, and
understand the reason why

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:55.210
it was important for good data.

00:17:55.210 --> 00:17:59.270
Because federal, and
state, and elections,

00:17:59.270 --> 00:18:01.120
get decided based on census.

00:18:01.120 --> 00:18:03.876
It's about redistricting,
and obviously, lately,

00:18:03.876 --> 00:18:04.750
about gerrymandering.

00:18:08.280 --> 00:18:11.290
That's true.

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:14.250
And it's about
allocations of resources.

00:18:14.250 --> 00:18:16.990
And data collection continues
to be something that's

00:18:16.990 --> 00:18:20.370
important in so
many ways in terms

00:18:20.370 --> 00:18:23.490
of how states
allocate resources,

00:18:23.490 --> 00:18:26.420
how the feds allocate resources.

00:18:26.420 --> 00:18:30.390
Once again, DC matters to
the home rule community,

00:18:30.390 --> 00:18:35.630
St. Paul, in Minnesota, matters
to the home rule community.

00:18:35.630 --> 00:18:38.070
Understanding that working
with federal agencies

00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:39.860
is also politics.

00:18:39.860 --> 00:18:44.430
Tribes actually, because of the
Federal Trust Responsibility--

00:18:44.430 --> 00:18:47.172
everybody know what the Federal
Trust Responsibility is?

00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:52.920
OK.

00:18:52.920 --> 00:18:56.712
So we prepaid for a
whole bunch of stuff.

00:18:56.712 --> 00:18:58.194
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:01.660 --> 00:19:04.310
We paid with the country.

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:07.020
And the promise was, if
we give up the country,

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:10.780
that some of-- that our
needs would be taken care of.

00:19:10.780 --> 00:19:16.900
That didn't go so well, but
we're kind of expecting it now.

00:19:16.900 --> 00:19:20.660
Our place in politics is about
saying the bill is coming due.

00:19:20.660 --> 00:19:22.770
We would like to
be self-determined,

00:19:22.770 --> 00:19:26.800
self-sufficient, and we would
like to carry our own water,

00:19:26.800 --> 00:19:29.070
and be truly
self-governing, and exercise

00:19:29.070 --> 00:19:32.610
that full political
status as sovereigns.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:33.700
And then guess what?

00:19:33.700 --> 00:19:37.180
Then you don't have to worry
about us too much anymore.

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:39.320
We want those
things for our self,

00:19:39.320 --> 00:19:44.280
just like every person and
family wants it for themselves.

00:19:44.280 --> 00:19:46.150
Working directly with
the federal government

00:19:46.150 --> 00:19:47.750
and the agencies as politics.

00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:49.540
At the top level you
have secretaries,

00:19:49.540 --> 00:19:51.980
and those are
political appointees.

00:19:51.980 --> 00:19:55.690
It matters who you elect.

00:19:55.690 --> 00:19:57.430
I'll use the current president.

00:19:57.430 --> 00:20:00.000
He has been the best
friend to Indian country

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.930
that we have ever seen
in the executive branch.

00:20:02.930 --> 00:20:05.640
We are on track to take
about a 1/2 a million

00:20:05.640 --> 00:20:09.780
more acres of tribal
homelands into trust,

00:20:09.780 --> 00:20:13.920
as well as having a fairly
robust agenda through each

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:18.950
of the departments around
strengthening Indian country.

00:20:18.950 --> 00:20:21.800
Consultation policies--
you will not do to us,

00:20:21.800 --> 00:20:22.970
you will do with us.

00:20:22.970 --> 00:20:26.870
We will communicate, we will
do negotiated rule-making,

00:20:26.870 --> 00:20:30.440
and we know how best to
serve our own communities.

00:20:30.440 --> 00:20:33.630
You have proven you're
not that good at it,

00:20:33.630 --> 00:20:35.950
so let's have this
conversation about how to get

00:20:35.950 --> 00:20:38.800
it done on a day-to-day basis.

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:43.680
We have institutionalized
the relationship, not just

00:20:43.680 --> 00:20:45.730
the ward status.

00:20:45.730 --> 00:20:49.820
We are a participant
in our own governance.

00:20:49.820 --> 00:20:52.180
Finally I'll talk a little
bit about Native peoples,

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:54.510
and Native politics,
and saying that,

00:20:54.510 --> 00:20:58.840
I am absolutely delighted,
as I look at social media,

00:20:58.840 --> 00:21:02.110
and I see tribal citizens
across the country taking

00:21:02.110 --> 00:21:06.970
that final step of
becoming candidates.

00:21:06.970 --> 00:21:09.320
It has been something that
has been woefully lacking.

00:21:09.320 --> 00:21:11.970
And we talked about this
in Indian country a lot

00:21:11.970 --> 00:21:13.640
about representation.

00:21:13.640 --> 00:21:17.280
Whether it's in our
classrooms, where our kids

00:21:17.280 --> 00:21:19.230
can see teachers
that look like them,

00:21:19.230 --> 00:21:22.910
and have curricula that's
reflective of them.

00:21:22.910 --> 00:21:27.100
We talk about it in social
services, family caseworkers,

00:21:27.100 --> 00:21:30.340
how do you know about the
dynamics in an Indian family,

00:21:30.340 --> 00:21:32.020
if you are not
culturally competent.

00:21:32.020 --> 00:21:34.890
And the quickest and easiest
way to get culturally competent

00:21:34.890 --> 00:21:38.070
is to be from the culture.

00:21:38.070 --> 00:21:41.390
This goes then to electoral
politics, as well.

00:21:41.390 --> 00:21:44.610
If we can change
voting in Minnesota,

00:21:44.610 --> 00:21:48.250
and elect an ally in
Al Franken, can we

00:21:48.250 --> 00:21:51.490
turn out the vote to elect
someone who looks just

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:55.300
like us, from our community,
to be representative

00:21:55.300 --> 00:21:58.970
of communities that
are largely Native.

00:21:58.970 --> 00:22:01.370
In the Southwest
we see candidates,

00:22:01.370 --> 00:22:05.330
we see them up in the Northwest.

00:22:05.330 --> 00:22:08.380
We have state legislatures
who are increasingly

00:22:08.380 --> 00:22:11.590
having people understand
that their road to higher

00:22:11.590 --> 00:22:14.280
elected office
starts in their home

00:22:14.280 --> 00:22:17.320
communities with local
seats, city council members,

00:22:17.320 --> 00:22:20.620
to statewide politics, and
hopefully, quite a number more

00:22:20.620 --> 00:22:22.210
at the federal level.

00:22:22.210 --> 00:22:25.540
Why does that matter to people
outside of Indian country?

00:22:25.540 --> 00:22:27.880
Our diversity is our strength.

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:30.440
By 2030 the majority
of this culture

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:33.180
will be people of color.

00:22:33.180 --> 00:22:35.270
And that wide
fabric of diversity

00:22:35.270 --> 00:22:37.070
is what makes us
strong, and it makes

00:22:37.070 --> 00:22:40.930
us resilient as a country,
but only if it's inclusive.

00:22:40.930 --> 00:22:42.810
We talk a lot at
the federal level

00:22:42.810 --> 00:22:47.080
of how do we compete against
China, and TPP, and everything

00:22:47.080 --> 00:22:48.200
else.

00:22:48.200 --> 00:22:49.870
A part of it is
making sure that we

00:22:49.870 --> 00:22:54.350
have a healthy and
participatory society, right?

00:22:54.350 --> 00:22:57.070
Because that's where the
solutions come to homegrown

00:22:57.070 --> 00:23:00.500
issues, and then bubble up,
and become our strength.

00:23:00.500 --> 00:23:03.404
So, vote Indian.

00:23:03.404 --> 00:23:04.268
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:04.268 --> 00:23:06.580
You know you want to.

00:23:06.580 --> 00:23:07.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:07.150 --> 00:23:09.440
You know you want to.

00:23:09.440 --> 00:23:13.910
Just in closing, all
politics is personal, right?

00:23:13.910 --> 00:23:16.440
Although you won't be seeing
me running for anything else

00:23:16.440 --> 00:23:19.000
anytime soon.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:22.000
That whole post-traumatic
stress thing.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:25.700
You know, understand that
politics for Indian country

00:23:25.700 --> 00:23:26.430
is personal.

00:23:26.430 --> 00:23:30.440
It becomes, first and foremost,
with the home rule community.

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:33.290
How can we become as
healthy as we can be,

00:23:33.290 --> 00:23:36.520
and as inclusive as we can
be in our home community.

00:23:36.520 --> 00:23:40.014
And then making that story more
broadly to other jurisdictions,

00:23:40.014 --> 00:23:41.930
where, hopefully, we'll
be talking to familiar

00:23:41.930 --> 00:23:44.280
faces in the future.

00:23:44.280 --> 00:23:47.810
And telling the story that
Native peoples-- our country

00:23:47.810 --> 00:23:51.080
is only as healthy as
those who have the least.

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:55.300
So let's bring that least up,
and work towards full equality.

00:23:55.300 --> 00:23:56.172
That's my job.

00:23:56.172 --> 00:23:56.880
Thank you, folks.

00:23:56.880 --> 00:23:58.359
[APPLAUSE]

00:24:03.300 --> 00:24:05.050
Hello, my name's
John Dossett, I'm

00:24:05.050 --> 00:24:07.230
with the National Congress
of American Indians.

00:24:07.230 --> 00:24:09.805
Thanks very much
for having me here.

00:24:09.805 --> 00:24:11.680
I thought before I
started-- my presentation,

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:15.140
I was really going to leap
right into sort of recent events

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:18.316
in working with Congress,
and the administration,

00:24:18.316 --> 00:24:20.440
getting a lot of policy
things done, but I thought,

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:22.300
maybe, first, I should tell you
a little bit about the National

00:24:22.300 --> 00:24:24.060
Congress of American Indians.

00:24:24.060 --> 00:24:26.481
NCAI is a membership
organization of Indian tribes

00:24:26.481 --> 00:24:27.730
from around the United States.

00:24:27.730 --> 00:24:30.700
There's about 250 member
tribes, that varies

00:24:30.700 --> 00:24:32.829
a little bit from year to year.

00:24:32.829 --> 00:24:34.870
The tribes get together
about three times a year,

00:24:34.870 --> 00:24:36.550
and they pass
resolutions, and then

00:24:36.550 --> 00:24:39.410
those resolutions are--
they're the marching orders

00:24:39.410 --> 00:24:41.730
for the staff of NCAI,
what we're supposed

00:24:41.730 --> 00:24:43.880
to try to achieve with
Congress, and what

00:24:43.880 --> 00:24:45.940
we try to achieve collectively.

00:24:45.940 --> 00:24:47.660
The mission statement,
or the preamble

00:24:47.660 --> 00:24:49.700
to the NCAI constitution
says that our goal

00:24:49.700 --> 00:24:51.940
is to advance
tribal sovereignty,

00:24:51.940 --> 00:24:56.770
and respect for tribal laws,
treaty rights, and the Federal

00:24:56.770 --> 00:24:59.360
Trust Responsibility.

00:24:59.360 --> 00:25:02.000
To promote the common
welfare of Indian people,

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:05.730
and educate the public towards
a better understanding.

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:09.000
So that's the broad
goals of NCAI.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:12.240
And NCAI, over the
years, formed in 1944,

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:14.600
fought against
termination, then pushed

00:25:14.600 --> 00:25:16.450
the self-determination policy.

00:25:16.450 --> 00:25:18.610
And since then NCAI
has probably been

00:25:18.610 --> 00:25:22.620
involved in most of the major
laws and regulations that

00:25:22.620 --> 00:25:26.220
have-- working to
advance Indian policy.

00:25:26.220 --> 00:25:29.010
So with that, I guess I'll
turn to my next subject.

00:25:29.010 --> 00:25:31.010
And I guess it was,
you know, when I first

00:25:31.010 --> 00:25:33.010
talked about this with
Maggie McKinley, Maggie--

00:25:33.010 --> 00:25:36.230
she wanted me to talk about
Indian tribal leaders,

00:25:36.230 --> 00:25:39.000
and NCAI, and how we
work on lobbying issues,

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.950
and that we need to reclaim
the language of lobbying.

00:25:41.950 --> 00:25:44.260
And I thought-- it was a
little bit dissonant for me

00:25:44.260 --> 00:25:46.910
because, I don't think
tribal leaders have ever

00:25:46.910 --> 00:25:50.850
thought of lobbying as
anything but 100% good.

00:25:50.850 --> 00:25:54.440
Lobbying, it isn't some--
it isn't a thing where

00:25:54.440 --> 00:25:57.230
there's-- it's not shady
or corrupt, I mean,

00:25:57.230 --> 00:26:00.250
maybe that's something in
other parts of America that--

00:26:00.250 --> 00:26:02.650
but, I think tribal leaders
really see this as, you know,

00:26:02.650 --> 00:26:06.000
the right to petition for
the redress of grievances.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:09.640
They're in the mode
of advancing what--

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:12.760
trying to make good things
happen for their cultures,

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:14.530
and for their tribes back home.

00:26:14.530 --> 00:26:16.310
And I've never had
any sense that it's

00:26:16.310 --> 00:26:19.042
anything less than what
we ought to be doing.

00:26:19.042 --> 00:26:20.500
In fact, tribal
leaders consider it

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:22.630
