00:30:05.800 --> 00:30:07.850
And then coalition
building in Indian country.

00:30:07.850 --> 00:30:09.725
And that's really what
I'm going to focus on,

00:30:09.725 --> 00:30:11.020
it's coalition building.

00:30:11.020 --> 00:30:15.020
And here's a couple other
points, but keep it going.

00:30:15.020 --> 00:30:17.880
So I wanted to focus on one
coalition building effort that

00:30:17.880 --> 00:30:20.210
was a really important one,
that we were very honored

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:21.790
to work on.

00:30:21.790 --> 00:30:25.240
And I wanted to show this
photograph because I think

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:27.530
it emphasizes the coalition.

00:30:27.530 --> 00:30:30.450
You know, there's a
tendency, I think sometimes,

00:30:30.450 --> 00:30:33.450
as if, you know, there were one,
or two, charismatic people who

00:30:33.450 --> 00:30:36.160
got a lot of stuff
done, and it's,

00:30:36.160 --> 00:30:39.480
I think, maybe afterwards,
we impose that narrative

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:40.410
on what happened.

00:30:40.410 --> 00:30:42.460
But really when
it's going on it's

00:30:42.460 --> 00:30:45.610
a swarm of people all over the
country doing amazing things.

00:30:45.610 --> 00:30:48.190
And here's just an example
of part of that swarm.

00:30:48.190 --> 00:30:51.510
And there are many
different points in time

00:30:51.510 --> 00:30:53.820
when individuals
step up to the plate,

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:56.430
and they keep pushing the ball
forward in critical events,

00:30:56.430 --> 00:30:59.730
and it takes this whole
series of serendipitous events

00:30:59.730 --> 00:31:01.050
to get you to the point.

00:31:01.050 --> 00:31:04.520
And this expansion of tribal
jurisdiction over non-Indians

00:31:04.520 --> 00:31:05.955
of the Violence
Against Women Act,

00:31:05.955 --> 00:31:08.580
was really one of those things,
where a lot of different things

00:31:08.580 --> 00:31:10.870
came together, a lot of
people came together.

00:31:10.870 --> 00:31:13.315
It was really great
to be a part of it,

00:31:13.315 --> 00:31:14.940
and that's what I
wanted to talk about,

00:31:14.940 --> 00:31:18.490
is that kind of
coalition building.

00:31:18.490 --> 00:31:21.355
As background on this
issue, I think it-- maybe

00:31:21.355 --> 00:31:23.730
it started with the Tribal
Law and Order Act discussions,

00:31:23.730 --> 00:31:27.430
when, in 2007, they
started holding hearings.

00:31:27.430 --> 00:31:29.780
And this problem of
domestic violence

00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:33.046
committed by non-Indians really
began coming to the forefront.

00:31:33.046 --> 00:31:34.920
There were a lot of
hearings held in Congress

00:31:34.920 --> 00:31:37.070
during that time.

00:31:37.070 --> 00:31:40.340
And these facts kept coming
forward, 61% of Native women

00:31:40.340 --> 00:31:42.880
have been subject
to assault, that's

00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:44.700
triple the national rate.

00:31:44.700 --> 00:31:47.580
66% of the perpetrators
are non-Indian.

00:31:47.580 --> 00:31:49.600
There's this in-- the
federal government

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:52.570
is the only entity that has
jurisdiction over non-Indians,

00:31:52.570 --> 00:31:54.030
until recently, anyway.

00:31:54.030 --> 00:31:55.760
And there's this
incredibly high rate

00:31:55.760 --> 00:31:58.040
of declinations, where the
federal government won't

00:31:58.040 --> 00:32:00.600
prosecute these cases,
particularly domestic violence

00:32:00.600 --> 00:32:03.270
cases, because they're
kind of hard to prosecute.

00:32:03.270 --> 00:32:05.330
And that tribal governments
are the only entity

00:32:05.330 --> 00:32:08.960
that could provide
safety for Native women.

00:32:08.960 --> 00:32:11.380
So this proposed
remedy came forward

00:32:11.380 --> 00:32:14.120
to amend the Indian Civil
Rights Act to restore

00:32:14.120 --> 00:32:16.070
tribal jurisdiction
over non-Indians

00:32:16.070 --> 00:32:17.950
for domestic violence crimes.

00:32:17.950 --> 00:32:20.440
There were a whole bunch of
factors that fed into this,

00:32:20.440 --> 00:32:21.856
and I think, first
of all, we have

00:32:21.856 --> 00:32:25.640
to credit the VAWA movement more
generally across the country.

00:32:25.640 --> 00:32:28.290
I mean, they passed the Violence
Against Women Act in 1994,

00:32:28.290 --> 00:32:30.800
I think before tribes
were deeply involved.

00:32:30.800 --> 00:32:33.750
But the infrastructure
that they set up,

00:32:33.750 --> 00:32:37.340
particularly the shelters,
and then funding the shelters

00:32:37.340 --> 00:32:39.850
on Indian reservations,
funding the victims

00:32:39.850 --> 00:32:41.960
advocates around the country.

00:32:41.960 --> 00:32:44.930
That infrastructure,
I think, created

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:48.380
the basis for what then
went forward from there.

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:51.740
And some of that took
place in the NCAI Violence

00:32:51.740 --> 00:32:54.740
Against Women Task Force,
led by tribal leaders,

00:32:54.740 --> 00:32:56.720
like Juana Majel,
and Terri Henry,

00:32:56.720 --> 00:32:59.070
where they've been pushing
this issue probably

00:32:59.070 --> 00:33:00.930
since about 1999.

00:33:00.930 --> 00:33:04.140
So it really-- I guess one
point I want to get across

00:33:04.140 --> 00:33:08.030
is these kind of things, you may
think it all happened in 2013,

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:11.460
they started working on that
like a decade and a half

00:33:11.460 --> 00:33:13.476
to get to that point.

00:33:13.476 --> 00:33:15.850
There were some very important
studies, the Ninth Circuit

00:33:15.850 --> 00:33:19.470
Gender Bias Task Force
report that came out in 1997,

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:21.800
highlighted this problem,
and it was this really great,

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:24.650
you know, the Ninth Circuit
judges come out with a report,

00:33:24.650 --> 00:33:27.870
highlighting the issue,
from a long time ago.

00:33:27.870 --> 00:33:30.030
The fact that there was
now crime data-- crime

00:33:30.030 --> 00:33:32.240
data in Indian country
wasn't generally available

00:33:32.240 --> 00:33:34.760
until the Clinton administration
started collecting it.

00:33:34.760 --> 00:33:37.120
So that-- you know that data
that I just recited to you,

00:33:37.120 --> 00:33:38.300
that's pretty compelling?

00:33:38.300 --> 00:33:42.110
None of that existed
until before then.

00:33:42.110 --> 00:33:44.940
We had an NCAI
resolution as of 2003,

00:33:44.940 --> 00:33:48.210
the Lara case came along,
that Maze of Injustice report

00:33:48.210 --> 00:33:51.342
was incredibly important,
from Amnesty International.

00:33:51.342 --> 00:33:52.800
Anyway, there was
this whole series

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:55.050
of events that led to this.

00:33:55.050 --> 00:33:57.770
I probably think the most
important thing was native vote

00:33:57.770 --> 00:33:58.307
overall.

00:33:58.307 --> 00:33:59.765
When it came right
down to it, when

00:33:59.765 --> 00:34:01.806
we were trying to get the
bill through the house,

00:34:01.806 --> 00:34:04.360
you know, it was a Republican
House of Representatives,

00:34:04.360 --> 00:34:06.090
they weren't
generally supportive,

00:34:06.090 --> 00:34:07.882
but it was about finding
enough Republicans

00:34:07.882 --> 00:34:09.298
to go with the
Democrats, who were

00:34:09.298 --> 00:34:10.530
going to vote for the bill.

00:34:10.530 --> 00:34:14.179
So we got out the map, and
there are 63 Republicans who

00:34:14.179 --> 00:34:16.489
have Indian tribes
in their districts,

00:34:16.489 --> 00:34:19.394
and we started targeting them,
one after another, and flipping

00:34:19.394 --> 00:34:20.560
them over to the other side.

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:22.768
And then by the time we got
to about 60, it was like,

00:34:22.768 --> 00:34:25.850
OK, the bill headed to the
floor, and it went to a vote.

00:34:25.850 --> 00:34:29.159
So the fact that tribes
are turning out the vote,

00:34:29.159 --> 00:34:31.610
even if it's small
tribes in one district,

00:34:31.610 --> 00:34:34.280
it's just incredibly
important for politics.

00:34:34.280 --> 00:34:37.350
And in the end, that's
what got the bill done,

00:34:37.350 --> 00:34:41.270
and it showed itself
in this legislation.

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:43.679
This was a slide
that one of the-- I

00:34:43.679 --> 00:34:46.504
think the National Indian
Women's Resource Center,

00:34:46.504 --> 00:34:47.920
they had a
presentation about it--

00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:50.139
and this was as it was going on.

00:34:50.139 --> 00:34:54.250
And I just thought it was a nice
graphic of how the coalition

00:34:54.250 --> 00:34:55.340
building process works.

00:34:55.340 --> 00:34:57.580
I mean, it really isn't
one person, or one entity,

00:34:57.580 --> 00:35:00.690
it's everybody working together.

00:35:00.690 --> 00:35:04.630
This is a photograph of a group
of women in North Dakota--

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:06.740
South Dakota, who
are-- they were

00:35:06.740 --> 00:35:08.110
holding marches and rallies.

00:35:08.110 --> 00:35:11.590
I mean, this was going on all
across the country in 2012,

00:35:11.590 --> 00:35:12.830
and 2013.

00:35:12.830 --> 00:35:15.650
And it was like we're-- it
was like a social movement,

00:35:15.650 --> 00:35:17.960
you know, like people
heard about it.

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:21.870
It was the most exciting
thing I've been involved in.

00:35:21.870 --> 00:35:24.770
I wanted to-- Sarah Deer-- there
are probably some academics

00:35:24.770 --> 00:35:26.690
here in the crowd,
so there is a role

00:35:26.690 --> 00:35:28.160
for academics in this process.

00:35:28.160 --> 00:35:31.430
And Sarah Deer and her Maze of
Injustice Report, I thought,

00:35:31.430 --> 00:35:33.870
were very important in
moving this forward.

00:35:33.870 --> 00:35:36.390
But it wasn't those-- it wasn't
this report all by itself.

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:39.110
This was just one more piece
of the puzzle coming together

00:35:39.110 --> 00:35:41.100
so everybody can play a role.

00:35:41.100 --> 00:35:43.940
And you just have to watch
these issues and figure out

00:35:43.940 --> 00:35:47.500
the right timing, and
when to come forward.

00:35:47.500 --> 00:35:49.000
So this new law,
what it did is, it

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:50.490
affirmed tribal
inherent authority

00:35:50.490 --> 00:35:51.870
to exercise criminal
jurisdiction

00:35:51.870 --> 00:35:54.300
over domestic violence,
dating violence,

00:35:54.300 --> 00:35:56.240
and violation of
protection orders.

00:35:56.240 --> 00:35:58.190
Those violations of
protective orders

00:35:58.190 --> 00:36:00.940
aren't just intimate partners,
that could be anybody.

00:36:00.940 --> 00:36:02.670
So that's really, I
mean, in some ways

00:36:02.670 --> 00:36:05.320
people think that this is
fairly narrow jurisdiction,

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:06.970
but when you think
about this authority

00:36:06.970 --> 00:36:10.880
to criminally prosecute any
violation of protection order,

00:36:10.880 --> 00:36:13.670
you could get jurisdiction
over just about anyone,

00:36:13.670 --> 00:36:17.560
by first issuing a protection
order, and then enforcing it.

00:36:17.560 --> 00:36:19.940
There are 12 tribes who
are currently implementing,

00:36:19.940 --> 00:36:22.240
I think there are
more on the way.

00:36:22.240 --> 00:36:26.120
There have been more than
50 cases prosecuted to date.

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:27.850
So far the experience
shows that there

00:36:27.850 --> 00:36:31.610
have been some difficulties with
child victims, related crimes,

00:36:31.610 --> 00:36:34.120
like if you find a drug
crime at the same scene,

00:36:34.120 --> 00:36:37.460
and then, how violent
does it have to be?

00:36:37.460 --> 00:36:39.000
Exactly, what is violence?

00:36:39.000 --> 00:36:41.830
So there is already
legislation pending in Congress

00:36:41.830 --> 00:36:43.840
to address these issues
that got introduced

00:36:43.840 --> 00:36:44.970
a month, or two, ago.

00:36:44.970 --> 00:36:47.750
So I think that can show you
how this stuff, this ball,

00:36:47.750 --> 00:36:49.270
is continuing to roll.

00:36:49.270 --> 00:36:50.950
You know, now we have
data about what's

00:36:50.950 --> 00:36:53.140
going on in these--
at the 12 tribes

00:36:53.140 --> 00:36:56.250
who are already prosecuting, and
it continues to move forward,

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:59.230
and we're going
to keep it going.

00:36:59.230 --> 00:37:00.930
I'll skip past this one.

