One of the tricks
of lobbying is,

00:37:06.630 --> 00:37:08.671
when you're sitting in
front of a decision maker,

00:37:08.671 --> 00:37:10.370
like Karen Diver,
for instance, you

00:37:10.370 --> 00:37:11.920
might want to talk about
issues that are important you.

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:14.261
So I was going to highlight
a couple of other issues--

00:37:14.261 --> 00:37:14.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:14.760 --> 00:37:16.270
--that are coming up.

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:19.390
And this is more
coalition work that we all

00:37:19.390 --> 00:37:20.620
need to work together on.

00:37:20.620 --> 00:37:22.390
And there are some things
that we really want to submit.

00:37:22.390 --> 00:37:24.850
The administration has achieved
this amazing list of things,

00:37:24.850 --> 00:37:27.141
but there's a couple more
things we'd like to get done.

00:37:27.141 --> 00:37:30.310
One of them is to modernize
the Indian Trader Regulations.

00:37:30.310 --> 00:37:33.170
The secretary has authority
to regulate, basically,

00:37:33.170 --> 00:37:35.160
trade with the Indians
on reservations.

00:37:35.160 --> 00:37:36.670
And the administration's
been really

00:37:36.670 --> 00:37:39.520
great about asserting that in
the [INAUDIBLE] litigation,

00:37:39.520 --> 00:37:42.300
where the state is
collecting dual taxation

00:37:42.300 --> 00:37:43.300
on the reservation.

00:37:43.300 --> 00:37:44.820
And at least in my
opinion, this is

00:37:44.820 --> 00:37:47.300
the-- why are Indian
reservations always struggling

00:37:47.300 --> 00:37:48.200
economically?

00:37:48.200 --> 00:37:50.432
It's because the
states tax everything,

00:37:50.432 --> 00:37:52.140
and then they don't
provide any services,

00:37:52.140 --> 00:37:54.120
and then the tribes
can't tax on top of that.

00:37:54.120 --> 00:37:56.270
If tribes-- if you can
eliminate the state taxes,

00:37:56.270 --> 00:37:58.060
and tribe could collect
their own taxes,

00:37:58.060 --> 00:37:59.840
tribes could provide
taxes-- you know,

00:37:59.840 --> 00:38:01.660
services on the
reservation, just

00:38:01.660 --> 00:38:03.560
like most other
local communities do.

00:38:03.560 --> 00:38:05.810
But they've been unable to
do that because of a series

00:38:05.810 --> 00:38:07.740
of bad Supreme Court decisions.

00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:09.420
But there is this
proposal, pending

00:38:09.420 --> 00:38:10.970
at the Department of
Interior, that we'd really

00:38:10.970 --> 00:38:12.540
like them to move
forward on, that

00:38:12.540 --> 00:38:14.710
would empower tribal
business licensing,

00:38:14.710 --> 00:38:17.250
there would be consent to
tribal jurisdiction addressing

00:38:17.250 --> 00:38:21.820
the Dollar General case, and
would eliminate dual taxation.

00:38:21.820 --> 00:38:23.910
Another interesting one
that's going on right

00:38:23.910 --> 00:38:26.800
now is this Bears Ears
National Monument.

00:38:26.800 --> 00:38:30.480
This is also a coalition of five
tribes out of the Southwest.

00:38:30.480 --> 00:38:32.070
They are asking the
federal government

00:38:32.070 --> 00:38:34.153
to create a national
monument through presidential

00:38:34.153 --> 00:38:37.750
proclamation to set aside
1.9 million acres of very

00:38:37.750 --> 00:38:40.700
important tribal
cultural sacred lands,

00:38:40.700 --> 00:38:43.070
but to do it under
tribal code management,

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:45.320
under a code management
plan, it would really

00:38:45.320 --> 00:38:47.350
be an amazing step forward.

00:38:47.350 --> 00:38:49.440
Charles Wilkinson is
working with the tribes

00:38:49.440 --> 00:38:51.160
in that area on
this, so it's really

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:53.272
a very interesting development.

00:38:53.272 --> 00:38:54.730
So the last thing
I wanted to share

00:38:54.730 --> 00:38:57.640
with you is, this is the--
staff come in to NCAI,

00:38:57.640 --> 00:38:59.190
and they're like,
OK, what do we do?

00:38:59.190 --> 00:39:02.800
So this is the formula that--
I think we have at NCAI-- this

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:04.030
is what you do with your job.

00:39:04.030 --> 00:39:05.950
You study the issue, you've
got to know it really well,

00:39:05.950 --> 00:39:07.270
and you identify a solution.

00:39:07.270 --> 00:39:08.895
This is a lot more
work than you think,

00:39:08.895 --> 00:39:10.860
but this is basically
the part of it.

00:39:10.860 --> 00:39:13.167
Second, you've got to
identify the decision

00:39:13.167 --> 00:39:15.500
makers, and the process that
you're going to go through.

00:39:15.500 --> 00:39:17.041
Whether you're
working with Congress,

00:39:17.041 --> 00:39:19.440
which there's-- and there's
a process and rules for all

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:20.280
of this stuff.

00:39:20.280 --> 00:39:22.472
Also, working with the
agencies, so understanding

00:39:22.472 --> 00:39:24.430
those rules, and the
process, and how it works,

00:39:24.430 --> 00:39:26.054
it's not that much
different than being

00:39:26.054 --> 00:39:27.100
a lawyer in the courts.

00:39:27.100 --> 00:39:29.440
There's rules and a process.

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:31.600
You've got to have very
concise, short messages,

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:33.170
and make sure that
they're delivered.

00:39:33.170 --> 00:39:35.720
Know the timing, you get
them-- you got to deliver them,

00:39:35.720 --> 00:39:37.810
you do it early,
you do a follow up,

00:39:37.810 --> 00:39:40.420
and then right at the decision
time, you do it again.

00:39:40.420 --> 00:39:42.760
You share all this information
with your coalition,

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:44.660
and you ask them to do
the same things that

00:39:44.660 --> 00:39:46.460
they're-- everybody's
on the same page,

00:39:46.460 --> 00:39:49.100
putting all these messages in
front of the decision makers.

00:39:49.100 --> 00:39:51.370
And then you work with
media, and social media,

00:39:51.370 --> 00:39:54.275
to make sure that the message
spreads as far as you can.

00:39:54.275 --> 00:39:55.150
Anyway, there you go.

00:39:55.150 --> 00:39:57.490
That's the advocacy formula
that we use at NCAI.

00:39:57.490 --> 00:39:59.156
Thanks very much.

