01:07:20.290 --> 01:07:22.250
I think one of the
great advances,

01:07:22.250 --> 01:07:25.000
recently, was the passage of the
Indian Health Care Improvement

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:27.950
Act, as a part of the
Affordable Care Act.

01:07:27.950 --> 01:07:31.000
And tribes now have the ability
to define their own service

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:34.270
populations, and provide
services to anyone,

01:07:34.270 --> 01:07:35.740
and then to do
third-party billing,

01:07:35.740 --> 01:07:37.410
whether it's to
Medicare, or Medicaid,

01:07:37.410 --> 01:07:39.880
or the VA, or private insurance.

01:07:39.880 --> 01:07:44.240
And some tribes are becoming
regional health care providers.

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:46.180
I know of tribes out
in the Northwest,

01:07:46.180 --> 01:07:48.220
you know, they've got
26 doctors on staff,

01:07:48.220 --> 01:07:50.442
they're setting up facilities.

01:07:50.442 --> 01:07:51.900
At least, I think
that, that may be

01:07:51.900 --> 01:07:53.483
one of the great
opportunities coming,

01:07:53.483 --> 01:07:57.030
is for tribes to really expand
providing health care, not

01:07:57.030 --> 01:08:00.090
just to their own community,
but to everybody around them.

01:08:00.090 --> 01:08:02.090
And then through that
being able to increase

01:08:02.090 --> 01:08:04.170
the amount of services they can
provide to their own members,

01:08:04.170 --> 01:08:04.670
as well.

01:08:08.090 --> 01:08:10.300
-So we continue to
face a public health

01:08:10.300 --> 01:08:12.760
crisis in Indian country.

01:08:12.760 --> 01:08:14.480
The average age of
death in the 70s,

01:08:14.480 --> 01:08:18.020
for a Native American
person, was around 56.

01:08:18.020 --> 01:08:22.029
Now that number, I
believe, is in the low 70s,

01:08:22.029 --> 01:08:25.590
still well below the
national average.

01:08:25.590 --> 01:08:28.000
A lot of chronic
conditions, particularly

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:32.510
hit hard by diabetes,
which many attribute

01:08:32.510 --> 01:08:36.330
to the quick change in diet
in the reservation system.

01:08:36.330 --> 01:08:40.060
Additionally, the
reservations themselves,

01:08:40.060 --> 01:08:44.620
and how isolated they are,
and coupled with poverty,

01:08:44.620 --> 01:08:46.620
and things like that--
even though I was teasing

01:08:46.620 --> 01:08:50.950
him-- create food
deserts, and things

01:08:50.950 --> 01:08:54.069
like that, which they catch
up with you later, obviously,

01:08:54.069 --> 01:08:56.479
in terms of chronic conditions.

01:08:56.479 --> 01:09:01.319
Indian Health Service continues
to be funded at only about 48%

01:09:01.319 --> 01:09:02.930
of defined need.

01:09:02.930 --> 01:09:07.069
Before the Obama administration
it was in the 30s, 30%,

01:09:07.069 --> 01:09:10.340
so even though we've done
well, and getting it better,

01:09:10.340 --> 01:09:11.720
it's still not adequate.

01:09:11.720 --> 01:09:15.890
Attracting and retaining quality
staff in the Indian country

01:09:15.890 --> 01:09:18.480
remains a hardship,
because there's

01:09:18.480 --> 01:09:20.479
a lack of workforce,
housing-- so these are just

01:09:20.479 --> 01:09:22.920
like huge complex issues.

01:09:22.920 --> 01:09:24.830
On the other hand,
you've seen tribes

01:09:24.830 --> 01:09:26.330
under self-governance,
who have made

01:09:26.330 --> 01:09:30.229
huge inroads in terms
of public health,

01:09:30.229 --> 01:09:34.899
and really restructuring
how they deliver

01:09:34.899 --> 01:09:38.270
care, one, around cultural
competency, but also,

01:09:38.270 --> 01:09:39.825
really a holistic approach.

01:09:39.825 --> 01:09:41.450
You can go in and
get your ear checked,

01:09:41.450 --> 01:09:44.649
and they're going to check
your toes if you're diabetic.

01:09:44.649 --> 01:09:47.020
And even if you're
not diabetic, so

01:09:47.020 --> 01:09:49.710
that we're no longer
managing the outcomes,

01:09:49.710 --> 01:09:51.800
we're managing health.

01:09:51.800 --> 01:09:55.500
There's-- and getting back
to traditional food sources,

01:09:55.500 --> 01:09:59.370
you know, there's this big
cycle of what goes around comes

01:09:59.370 --> 01:10:03.100
around, and this ties
back to our, one,

01:10:03.100 --> 01:10:06.120
right to health care as part
of the Trust Responsibility,

01:10:06.120 --> 01:10:09.500
and a treaty right, but also
the ties that we have around

01:10:09.500 --> 01:10:12.420
managing natural resources,
and our rights to hunt, fish,

01:10:12.420 --> 01:10:13.340
and gather.

01:10:13.340 --> 01:10:15.810
And get our people back
to those traditional food

01:10:15.810 --> 01:10:21.270
sources, where it leads
to better health outcomes.

01:10:21.270 --> 01:10:23.909
But the quality of
that resource matters.

01:10:23.909 --> 01:10:25.450
We can't tell our
people to eat fish,

01:10:25.450 --> 01:10:28.100
if our fish have
too much mercury.

01:10:28.100 --> 01:10:30.290
We can't harvest wild
rice if the water

01:10:30.290 --> 01:10:33.050
is of such poor
condition that it

01:10:33.050 --> 01:10:36.970
reduces the quality
of the harvest,

01:10:36.970 --> 01:10:38.400
and on, and on, and on.

01:10:38.400 --> 01:10:40.250
So, it's not as
simple as saying,

01:10:40.250 --> 01:10:42.410
more doctors, more
health education,

01:10:42.410 --> 01:10:44.190
it is about being better.

01:10:44.190 --> 01:10:47.650
Being better to our planet,
being better to our community,

01:10:47.650 --> 01:10:50.640
making sure that they have
access, and the economics,

01:10:50.640 --> 01:10:52.760
to have a well-rounded
diet, and to be

01:10:52.760 --> 01:10:56.710
able to afford-- I bought an
apple the other day, it was $1.

01:10:56.710 --> 01:10:58.720
A whole dollar, you
know what I mean?

01:10:58.720 --> 01:11:01.730
And so, when we
tell our families,

01:11:01.730 --> 01:11:06.500
you need to have access
to fruits and vegetables,

01:11:06.500 --> 01:11:08.980
you need access to an
economy to make that happen,

01:11:08.980 --> 01:11:11.330
and too many of our
reservation communities

01:11:11.330 --> 01:11:15.960
still don't have as robust
access to a living wage.

01:11:18.530 --> 01:11:20.460
-The other thing I
would suggest is,

01:11:20.460 --> 01:11:23.710
being an ally to the
indigenous peoples,

01:11:23.710 --> 01:11:25.600
or the Original
Peoples close by here,

01:11:25.600 --> 01:11:28.310
and ask them, and approach
them, what is it that you need?

01:11:28.310 --> 01:11:29.700
What can we do to support you?

01:11:29.700 --> 01:11:32.100
They absolutely
have the answers.

01:11:32.100 --> 01:11:37.790
In my own community, after
I didn't get in for chief,

01:11:37.790 --> 01:11:39.630
I went-- I'm not
a political person

01:11:39.630 --> 01:11:42.690
by any stretch of
the imagination.

01:11:42.690 --> 01:11:45.000
I'm not an activist or
an environmentalist,

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:47.590
I am a defender and
protector of my homelands.

01:11:47.590 --> 01:11:51.740
When I was going door to
door, and I found this man

01:11:51.740 --> 01:11:55.840
in just a inhumane situation.

01:11:55.840 --> 01:11:57.540
He had been homeless
for 15 years,

01:11:57.540 --> 01:12:00.810
he dug a hole in the ground,
and basically put some boards

01:12:00.810 --> 01:12:01.860
together.

01:12:01.860 --> 01:12:06.040
And yet, our reserve
built a $450,000 church

01:12:06.040 --> 01:12:07.830
almost literally
right beside him.

01:12:07.830 --> 01:12:13.980
See, there's these-- just
a conflict in ideology.

01:12:13.980 --> 01:12:17.670
Anyway, I told him, even if
I don't get in for chief,

01:12:17.670 --> 01:12:20.990
I was going to see
what I could do.

01:12:20.990 --> 01:12:23.873
I don't want to leave you the
impression that I work alone,

01:12:23.873 --> 01:12:25.100
I don't.

01:12:25.100 --> 01:12:27.450
I just have an idea and
some brilliant people

01:12:27.450 --> 01:12:29.060
bring it to life.

01:12:29.060 --> 01:12:33.690
I work with really incredibly,
incredibly powerful corps

01:12:33.690 --> 01:12:35.160
of people.

01:12:35.160 --> 01:12:37.660
And we decided that
we would fund-raise.

01:12:37.660 --> 01:12:41.480
So we fund-raised for him,
and we raised about $25,000.

01:12:41.480 --> 01:12:45.480
And today he has a mini
home that's self-sustaining,

01:12:45.480 --> 01:12:50.800
and it's built from material
that is eco-friendly.

01:12:50.800 --> 01:12:54.410
So now he has a home,
but it's healthy.

01:12:54.410 --> 01:12:59.650
But you should see him
today, he's about 45,

01:12:59.650 --> 01:13:01.560
but he looks much
older than that.

01:13:01.560 --> 01:13:05.740
Because that's what stress
and injustice does to people,

01:13:05.740 --> 01:13:07.890
it ages them.

01:13:07.890 --> 01:13:12.310
But today he has a home,
and it's off the grid.

01:13:12.310 --> 01:13:15.634
All of us will go without
power, but he won't even notice.

01:13:15.634 --> 01:13:16.900
[LAUGHTER]

01:13:16.900 --> 01:13:19.342
He has a wood stove that
can generate electricity,

01:13:19.342 --> 01:13:20.190
-Cool.

01:13:20.190 --> 01:13:21.700
-Right?

01:13:21.700 --> 01:13:23.900
That's the law of our people.

01:13:23.900 --> 01:13:27.690
You live it, you don't just
talk about it, you live it.

01:13:27.690 --> 01:13:31.640
If you see injustice you try
to do something about it.

01:13:31.640 --> 01:13:36.780
And I do little actions to try
and live our self-determination

01:13:36.780 --> 01:13:38.490
already.

01:13:38.490 --> 01:13:40.960
But reach out to the indigenous
people, to the Original

01:13:40.960 --> 01:13:42.970
Peoples, and ask
them, what can we

01:13:42.970 --> 01:13:47.830
do to support you in abolishing
the Doctrine of Discovery?

01:13:47.830 --> 01:13:51.140
So that there's a way
to begin the dialogue,

01:13:51.140 --> 01:13:53.710
to get your lands back, so
that you get your health back.

01:13:53.710 --> 01:13:58.210
Because shelter, health, land,
is everything, everything.

01:14:00.840 --> 01:14:05.300
-Unfortunately-- can you make
your question very, very brief?

01:14:05.300 --> 01:14:07.850
I'll make it as brief as I
possibly can, is that OK?

01:14:07.850 --> 01:14:09.410
-Yeah.

01:14:09.410 --> 01:14:11.382
-I'm Jamie Bissonnette Lewey.

01:14:11.382 --> 01:14:14.340
I'm Abenaki, from
Odanak First Nation,

01:14:14.340 --> 01:14:17.140
but I'm also the chair of
the Maine Indian Tribal State

01:14:17.140 --> 01:14:18.380
Commission.

01:14:18.380 --> 01:14:22.220
And as-- many of the
Northeast tribes,

01:14:22.220 --> 01:14:25.810
here, are subject to restrictive
settlement acts, which are more

01:14:25.810 --> 01:14:28.730
onerous than Public Law 280.

01:14:28.730 --> 01:14:32.900
I'm wondering, Sylvia,
if you could comment

01:14:32.900 --> 01:14:39.850
on the impact that acknowledged
treaty reservations might have

01:14:39.850 --> 01:14:45.740
on these laws, and the
protections, and preservation,

01:14:45.740 --> 01:14:48.580
of existence and
natural resources?

01:14:48.580 --> 01:14:51.690
Because in the laws--
is the treaties.

01:14:51.690 --> 01:14:56.950
And then, perhaps,
attorney Dossett,

01:14:56.950 --> 01:15:03.160
how the settlement
acts impact both VAWA,

01:15:03.160 --> 01:15:09.970
and Collins Colloquy
on the Stafford Act?

01:15:09.970 --> 01:15:12.220
Thank you.

01:15:12.220 --> 01:15:14.790
-I would suggest--
and this is what's

01:15:14.790 --> 01:15:17.270
happening in my
homelands over there,

01:15:17.270 --> 01:15:19.790
and that's what
started, Idle No More.

01:15:19.790 --> 01:15:23.510
It was us talking about
our inherent structures,

01:15:23.510 --> 01:15:25.390
and our laws.

01:15:25.390 --> 01:15:28.130
Now, the Canadian
government is inviting us

01:15:28.130 --> 01:15:30.840
to the table saying, hey,
let's talk about your laws,

01:15:30.840 --> 01:15:32.810
how can we apply them?

01:15:32.810 --> 01:15:36.050
But we have to be
careful in how it--

01:15:36.050 --> 01:15:42.250
is it going to be immersed
into that colonial, artificial,

01:15:42.250 --> 01:15:45.240
structure of governance, right?

01:15:45.240 --> 01:15:47.290
Is it going to get
assimilated in there,

01:15:47.290 --> 01:15:49.630
or is it going to be
a separate entity?

01:15:49.630 --> 01:15:53.770
And this is going to be a
dialogue for all indigenous,

01:15:53.770 --> 01:15:55.270
or Original Peoples.

01:15:55.270 --> 01:15:58.640
And I suggest to you
to begin revisiting,

01:15:58.640 --> 01:16:00.600
what are your laws to the water?

01:16:00.600 --> 01:16:02.910
What are your laws to the land?

01:16:02.910 --> 01:16:09.770
What is your constitution
that must begin incorporating

01:16:09.770 --> 01:16:11.570
all of these laws?

01:16:11.570 --> 01:16:13.530
And I talk about
that in my book.

01:16:13.530 --> 01:16:16.480
And if you could get
a hold of my book,

01:16:16.480 --> 01:16:20.500
and it's available through my
publisher, Purich Publishing.

01:16:20.500 --> 01:16:22.600
And you could use
it as a template.

01:16:22.600 --> 01:16:25.380
I'm not saying is the
answer to everything,

01:16:25.380 --> 01:16:28.770
but at least it
will guide a seed

01:16:28.770 --> 01:16:32.330
into beginning to
talk about your laws.

01:16:32.330 --> 01:16:36.140
Because we're not a lawless
people, we are not lawless.

01:16:36.140 --> 01:16:38.150
We have beautiful laws.

01:16:38.150 --> 01:16:41.370
And they weren't perfect,
but they're beautiful,

01:16:41.370 --> 01:16:42.124
and they did work.

01:16:42.124 --> 01:16:44.540
And those are the kind of
things that your community needs

01:16:44.540 --> 01:16:45.720
to talk about.

01:16:45.720 --> 01:16:47.720
We need to start
acting like nations.

01:16:50.660 --> 01:16:52.720
-On the Stafford Act--
just very quickly--

01:16:52.720 --> 01:16:55.135
I think that what you mention
is a very good example

01:16:55.135 --> 01:16:57.010
of the problem with the
Maine Settlement Act.

01:16:57.010 --> 01:16:59.594
That when the Stafford
Act came through,

01:16:59.594 --> 01:17:02.010
there actually was this debate
with the Maine legislators,

01:17:02.010 --> 01:17:04.080
like, should the
Maine tribes really be

01:17:04.080 --> 01:17:06.510
able to-- if there's a
flood, or a storm, you know,

01:17:06.510 --> 01:17:09.460
should they be able to get a
disaster declaration so they

01:17:09.460 --> 01:17:10.770
could get emergency relief?

01:17:10.770 --> 01:17:13.270
And people in the state were
like questioning whether that's

01:17:13.270 --> 01:17:15.000
a good idea, like, you know,
the state should really

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:16.420
have jurisdiction over them.

01:17:16.420 --> 01:17:18.570
I think the colloquy
was intended

01:17:18.570 --> 01:17:21.620
to help the tribes in
Maine get over that.

01:17:21.620 --> 01:17:24.300
But I think it's just an
example of what a problem

01:17:24.300 --> 01:17:26.780
the Maine Settlement Act
is, and it's something

01:17:26.780 --> 01:17:28.650
we need to keep working on.

01:17:28.650 --> 01:17:30.480
-Thank you.

01:17:30.480 --> 01:17:33.270
Karen Diver, John
Dossett, Sylvia McAdam,

01:17:33.270 --> 01:17:34.212
thank you so much.

01:17:34.212 --> 01:17:36.610
[APPLAUSE]

